	"introduction": {
		"title": "Vietnamese Modal Verbs",
		"content": [
			"Vietnamese modal verbs express necessity, possibility, ability, permission, and willingness. Unlike English, they always come BEFORE the main verb—no exceptions.",
			"The critical distinction: Vietnamese has separate modals for 'learned ability' (biết), 'permission/acquired ability' (được), and 'general possibility' (có thể). English 'can' maps to all three depending on context.",
			"Modal verbs in Vietnamese are simpler structurally than English but require precision in choosing the right modal for the intended meaning."
		]
	},
